            <section
              id="post-151"
              class="post-151 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-business"
            >
              <div class="row">
                <div class="span2 meta">
                  <p class="date">25 Jan 2008</p>
                  <p class="author">by Noel</p>
                </div>

                <div class="span8">
                  <h2>
                    <a
                      href="/untyping/2008/01/25/spin-farming-franchising-and-the-future-of-software-frameworks/"
                      rel="bookmark"
                      title="Permanent Link to SPIN-Farming, Franchising, and the Future of Software Frameworks"
                      >SPIN-Farming, Franchising, and the Future of Software
                      Frameworks</a
                    >
                  </h2>

                  <div class="entry">
                    <p>
                      Ever thought about buying a franchise? Like the idea of
                      running<br />
                      your own business but don’t want the risk of trying it all<br
                      />
                      alone? How about farming? Attracted by the notion of<br />
                      growing all your own food, and connecting with nature? How<br
                      />
                      about both — franchised farming? Sounds unlikely, but<br
                      />
                      that’s essentially what SPIN farming is.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The core of SPIN farming is, well, farming, but not on<br
                      />
                      the scale that most people associate with modern farming<br
                      />
                      techniques. SPIN farmers typically work plots less<br />
                      than an acre in area, and achieve good returns by<br />
                      concentrating on the most profitable crops, and utilising<br
                      />
                      crop rotation to increase yield. The best<br />
                      description I’ve found is&lt;a<br />
                      href=&#8221;http://www.celsias.com/2007/02/07/spin-farming-part-ii-heeding-the-call-to-farm/&#8221;&gt;here,<br
                      />
                      though it isn’t very detailed.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      In itself the farming techniques aren’t that radical. I<br
                      />
                      remember learning in high school that crop rotation was one<br
                      />
                      of the key innovations of the agrarian revoluation, and that<br
                      />
                      was some time ago (both high school, and the agrarian<br
                      />
                      revolution). What is novel is the way the SPIN farming<br
                      />
                      business is run, and that’s what causes me to call it a<br
                      />
                      franchise. Contained in the guide books (the&lt;a<br />
                      href=&#8221;http://www.spinfarming.com/buy/&#8221;&gt;complete
                      set can<br />
                      all be purchased online) is everything you’d expect from a<br
                      />
                      good franchise: a business plan, marketing advice, and a<br
                      />
                      detailed day-to-day workflow. In standardising the product<br
                      />
                      and creating a reproducible process it really isn’t any<br
                      />
                      different from McDonalds. Now SPIN farming isn’t a true<br
                      />
                      franchise — you don’t buy the right to use the name,<br />
                      and there isn’t any ongoing fee. And there’s no equivalent<br
                      />
                      to&lt;a<br />
                      href=&#8221;http://www.mcdonalds.com/corp/career/hamburger_university.html&#8221;&gt;Hamburger<br
                      />
                      University either. At least not yet. It is still an interesting
                      business<br />
                      model and one that I think has great potential, though<br
                      />
                      perhaps not for the financial gain of the founders.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      The franchise idea, believe it or not, has great<br />
                      relevance to computing. What is&lt;a<br />
                      href=&#8221;http://softwareengineering.vazexqi.com/files/pattern.html&#8221;&gt;convention<br
                      />
                      over configuration if not the computing equivalent of<br
                      />
                      the franchise’s reproducable process? Perhaps by regarding<br
                      />
                      frameworks as franchises we can shift the emphasis from<br
                      />
                      technical development to supporting the developer in every<br
                      />
                      way they need to succeed. This seems to me a better goal<br
                      />
                      for both framework developers and users.
                    </p>
                  </div>

